Having a Biblical worldview is the key!

!! What is Justice?
Justice is a good thing. Keys are called to uphold it. There are hundreds of references to justice. Receiving a result that is right and proper.

The basic meaning of justice is to be able to treat people fairly regarding marriage and social class.

Kevin DeYoung: "following the rule of law, showing impartiality, paying what you promised, not stealing, not swindling, not taking bribes, and not taking advantage of the weak because they are too uninformed or unconnected to stop you."

The New Testament words of justice is impartial. Biblical justice perhaps can also be defined: the impartial definition of God's Law.

The world so often redefines terms in order to better stand.

!!!! List of Biblical Justice
* Punishing the evildoer and violent man, Romans 13:4
* He who lives by the sword will die by the sword, Matthew 26:52
* Protecting the innocent and the weak, Romans 13:3
* Submitting to authority (even Nero), 1 Peter 2:13
* Values the importance of work, 2 Thessalonians 3:10
* Live quietly and mind your own affairs, 1 Thessalonians 4:11
* Pray for those in authority, 1 Timothy 2:1-2
* Do not associate with those given to change, Proverbs 24:21
* Biblical understandings of marriage, divorce, family, gender
* Hates partiality, corruption, differing weights and measures, double standards, hypocrisy, Proverbs 20:10, Matthew 7:5

!!! Must we do justice?
The church corporately and believers individually. We teach that the church is a unique organism made of by all born again believers. The church is distinct from Israel. The promises that God has made in the Israel will be fulfilled in Israel vice versa.

There is actually a great danger in trying to assume that the church has other obligations. The entire discipleship of the church gets diverted. These goals might be fine and good things, they are not the mission of the church. Whenever church tries to objectivize certain situations, there appears to be a failed effort due to sin. The culture is never redeemed and the Gospel is ultimately compromised.

Is proverty an implied missions of the church?

Only God will make all things new in His perfect timing. He will accomplish all things in His power and glory. Without any explicit commands, does that mean we as Christians don't have to do justice?

!!! Examples of Christian Calls to Justice?
* Matthew 7:12
* Luke 6:36
* Matthew 5:16
* Galatians 6:10

We are told to give opportunity to fellow Christians. The concept is starting to get very very close. These verses tend to be broad. We have broad and general commands to broad and general category of biblical Justice. Then...

!!! How should we do justice?
Same thing how we decide anything else in our lives? What friends do we make? Who should we marry? The commands on doing justice do not give us the specific direction as the time and place that tells us.

Matthew 25:14-30; how much time and money does our God allow us to take? You buy something and the cashier undercuts you. You receive terrible service in the restaurant.

There is this notion that the church itself is a just and impartial place. Matthew 18:15-17

Beyond that is whether or not you are making existing responsibilities. When you are working, are you being excellent at work? Are you involved in evangelism being the Gospel to our neighbors. Are you involved in the local church? Submitting to the leaders and showing to each others the love that we have for each other.

